3.3.1 Questions 1-5:

  1. This code is written incorrectly because the color argument is specific and cannot be inside the “aes” argument. Instead it should be written like this ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = “blue”)

  2. Categorical variables: Manufacturer, Model, Trans, drv, fl, and class. Continuous variables: displ, year, cyl, cty, and hwy. You can tell from the main mpg run because it tells you what is stored in Int or Dbl.

  3. A continuous variable can not be mapped to shape. R will behave different depending on if you want to map a continuous or categorical variable.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ, size = displ,))

  1. When mapping the same variable to multiple aesthetics, it will still run and it will give you an even better understanding of the difference between each of the different vairable points. For example, this chunk of code will return bigger and lighter points for the higher the value of cty.

ggplot(data = mpg) + + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = cty, size = cty))

  1. The stroke aesthetic can modify the width of a border.

  2. When you map something like aes(colour = displ < 5), it will plot two colors, one for when displ is less than 5 and one for when displ is greater than or equal to 5.

Section 3.5.1: #4 and #5 only

  1. The advantage of using a faceted plot instead of a color plot is that we get to see each individual class’s data points on it’s own plot. This is useful because if we had them all on the same plot, it could get crowded and sometimes it’s hard to differential the colors of each class. The disadvantage is that it’s a overwhelming to look at so many different plots and it is hard to compare the points against each other. The less data points, it seems that it would be better to have a color plot on one graph. If there are more data points, it could get crowded and it would be better to put it in a faceted plot

  2. nrow and ncol are the number of rows and columns. Shrink, switch, scales, and labeller are all other arguments that control layout of panels. Facet_grid() does not have nrow and ncol arguments because it is a matrix of one row and one column which are best combined when those combinations exist. Also, you can have forumals for rows and columns.

  1. geom_col() will add a bar chart instead of points, as we have normally done so. Col will show column like figures and can take the count of instances of that specific vairable. geom_bar() is a stat_count type function and will make the height of the bar porportional to the count of each data point.
